{"type":"message","id":"f49acd8c","parentId":"0e0593cd","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:08:50.540Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_vsx57nrdgd3u_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 100757\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: scripts/tic_experiment.ps1 (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and decide on ONE concrete action.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE\r\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE (Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec)\r\n- CFI Analysis is DONE (2026-03-24)\r\n- Next pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe key insight from CFI_RESULTS.md:\r\n- 44.8% of invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise/metaprogramming artifacts)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe next step is clear: implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would:\r\n1. Weight invariants by their CFI score\r\n2. Compare prediction accuracy vs frequency baseline\r\n3. Test if high-CFI invariants are better predictors\r\n\r\nLet me create an experiment script that:\r\n1. Loads the frequency-invariant data\r\n2. Applies CFI weighting\r\n3. Compares next-pulse prediction accuracy\r\n\r\nFirst, I need to look at what data is available. The CFI_RESULTS.md mentions there are analysis scripts. Let me check if there's a scripts directory or if I need to create the experiment from scratch.\r\n\r\nLooking at the file structure mentioned:\r\n- research/CFI_RESULTS.md - exists\r\n- research/ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md - exists\r\n- research/GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md - exists\r\n\r\nI should create a CFI-weighted compression experiment. The most concrete action would be to:\r\n1. Create an experiment script that tests CFI-weighted vs frequency-only compression\r\n2. Or create the compression baseline that will be used in the comparison\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the pending items more carefully:\r\n- \"CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\"\r\n\r\nThe most concrete next action is to create the experiment that compares these two approaches. I'll create a Python script that:\r\n\r\n\r\nI'll develop a systematic approach to test CFI-weighted compression. The script will generate synthetic data with known causal structure, enabling a clear comparison between frequency-based and CFI-weighted prediction methods. By creating a controlled experimental framework, I can objectively evaluate which compression technique provides more accurate next-pulse predictions.\r\n\r\nThe experiment will focus on:\r\n- Generating test data with predefined causal relationships\r\n- Implementing two compression strategies\r\n- Measuring prediction accuracy for each method\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 94.3% of frequency-invariants have low causal fidelity (CFI<0.7), meaning frequency-based compression is mostly capturing metaprogramming artifacts rather than true research trajectory. A controlled experiment is needed to quantify the predictive advantage of CFI-weighting.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a controlled experiment script that generates synthetic pulse sequences with known causal structure, then compares next-pulse prediction accuracy between CFI-weighted compression vs frequency-only baseline.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: #!/usr/bin/env python3\r\n\"\"\"\r\nCFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\nCompares next-pulse prediction accuracy: CFI-weighted vs frequency-only compression\r\n\r\nHypothesis: CFI-weighted compression should outperform frequency-only\r\nbecause it preserves causal research trajectory invariants.\r\n\"\"\"\r\n\r\nimport random\r\nfrom collections import Counter\r\nimport json\r\n\r\n# Seed for reproducibility\r\nrandom.seed(42)\r\n\r\n# ============================================================================\r\n# SYNTHETIC DATA GENERATOR\r\n# ============================================================================\r\n\r\ndef generate_pulse_sequence(n_pulses=100, causal_ratio=0.3):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Generate synthetic pulse sequence with controllable causal structure.\r\n    \r\n    - causal_tokens: appear in semantically related pulses (true research trajectory)\r\n    - noise_tokens: appear randomly (metaprogramming artifacts)\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    causal_tokens = [f\"causal_{i}\" for i in range(20)]\r\n    noise_tokens = [f\"noise_{i}\" for i in range(80)]\r\n    \r\n    pulses = []\r\n    for i in range(n_pulses):\r\n        pulse = []\r\n        # Add 2-4 causal tokens (based on previous pulse's causal content)\r\n        n_causal = random.randint(2, 4)\r\n        if i > 0 and random.random() < 0.8:  # 80% chance of causal continuity\r\n            prev_causal = [t for t in pulses[-1] if t.startswith(\"causal_\")]\r\n            if prev_causal:\r\n                pulse.extend(random.sample(prev_causal, min(n_causal, len(prev_causal))))\r\n        pulse.extend(random.sample(causal_tokens, n_causal))\r\n        \r\n        # Add 5-10 noise tokens (random, no temporal structure)\r\n        n_noise = random.randint(5, 10)\r\n        pulse.extend(random.sample(noise_tokens, n_noise))\r\n        \r\n        random.shuffle(pulse)\r\n        pulses.append(pulse)\r\n    \r\n    return pulses\r\n\r\n# ============================================================================\r\n# COMPRESSION METHODS\r\n# ============================================================================\r\n\r\ndef compute_frequencies(pulses):\r\n    \"\"\"Standard frequency-based compression (like current Breakaway).\"\"\"\r\n    all_tokens = [t for pulse in pulses for t in pulse]\r\n    freq = Counter(all_tokens)\r\n    return freq\r\n\r\ndef compute_cfi(pulses, window=5):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Compute Causal Fidelity Index for each token.\r\n    \r\n    CFI = probability token appears in context of its own causal cluster\r\n    vs random appearance in corpus.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    all_tokens = [t for pulse in pulses for t in pulse]\r\n    total_count = len(all_tokens)\r\n    corpus_freq = Counter(all_tokens)\r\n    \r\n    cfi_scores = {}\r\n    for token in corpus_freq:\r\n        # Count appearances in causal-adjacent context\r\n        causal_count = 0\r\n        for i, pulse in enumerate(pulses):\r\n            if token in pulse:\r\n                # Check if previous pulse had related causal tokens\r\n                for j in range(max(0,\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:08:28\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774361330537}}
